# Sensor Recording/Actuation

## Overview:

- --Program sends data between RFID device and motor
- --Relevent data from each attempt is stored on the attempts table of the database, including tag id, room id, date and if it was valid or not
- --Each attempt is checked against a validtags table on the server to see if the tag id/reader id combination is together in a row before moving the lock. If the combination is not in the validtags table the motor will not be moved, but a failed attempt will be logged.
- --One card will not open multiple doors at once. A different topic for each room is not required because it checks if a card is valid with a specific reader id which would be unique to a room. Requests are sent to one MQTT topic, with subscribers in the lock codebase receiving all requests and checking if the readerid matches their assigned reader using the doorlookup table.
- --All data that is transferred is in JSON format

# Mobile Phone App Integration

## Overview:

- --The app has a button to open the lock
- --The app verifies the user using the phone&#39;s IMEI number and submitting this as the tagid for validation. For demonstration purposes the IMEI number is hardcoded.
- --The app is able to to send (input attempts) and receive (check validation) data from the server
- --All data is exchanged in JSON format.

# Design of a Sensor Network to Control Water Valves for Garden Sprinklers

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

## Overview

This network is designed to allow a user to easily control the water valves on their garden sprinklers by using a variety of automation technologies. The user can activate them using the Samsung SmartThings app, which utilises Samsung&#39;s cloud servers or using a voice command issued to the Echo Dot running Amazon Alexa. It is also possible to have the valves open when the moisture of the soil gets to a certain level using the moisture sensor in each node.

### Network Topology

The system is primarily designed with range, convenience and reliablility in mind. It achieves this by running in a mesh network which provides greater range as each device does not have to communicate directly with the central hub because they can each act as repeaters for the network, passing the signal onto another device. This allows much greater distance coverage which might be necessary in a larger environment, or one that has a lot of obstructions to the signal. Using a mesh network topology is superior to something like a star network, as it introduces redundancy, meaning if one device fails it won&#39;t affect any other device.

## Nodes

Each node consists of five key components:

1. Arduino Uno Rev 3  This is the core mictrocontroller and memory component responsible for processing requests and passing them onto the valve. This is where the code and all runtime variables will be stored.
2. Z-Uno Arduino Z-Wave Adapter  This component provides the Arduino with the capabilities of communicating over Z-Wave and will handle all of it&#39;s wireless communications. Z-Wave is ideal because it is very low power and will prolong our battry life.
3. Electric Solenoid Valve  This component is required for opening and closing the valve once the signal has been received.
4. DFRobot Analog Soil Moisture Sensor for Arduino  This will allow the Arduino to measure the moisture levels in the soil, allowing for alerts and sprinkler automation if the soil becomes too dry.
5. Pealiker Waterproof Solar 25000mAH Powerbank  This will be responsible for powering the Arduino and all of the components attached to it. Waterproofing is important since it will be outside and likely get somewhat wet and damaged otherwise. This component has four small solar panels that unfold, which should significantly prolong how long it will last compared to a standard powerbank  ideally it would be fully manually charged before installation.

## Wireless Communication &amp; Data Exchange

The majority of data transfer between devices to and from the router will be done over HTTPS in JSON format. We use HTTPS for increased security of all communications and preventing malicious parties from gathering or interfering with data being transferred. Using JSON allows data being transferred to be easily parsed by the recipient.

For any node connecting to the SmartThings hub, all data will be transferred using Z-Wave; the adapters on each node allow them to send and receive Z-Wave communications.

### Why Z-Wave?

- --Z-Wave over WiFi for extremely low power consumption.
- --Samsung SmartThings Hub supports both Z-Wave and ZigBee but we choose Z-Wave over ZigBee because Z-Wave uses a lower frequency than ZigBee (908MHz vs 2.4GHz). Lower frequency means longer range and a higher frequency is not required for a water sprinkler use case and the longer range is more important for a garden scenario.
- --Uses AES 128 Encryption standard to secure wireless signals from attackers. Z-Wave Alliance makes it mandatory that all Z-Wave certified devices have an implementation of their Security 2 framework, greatly decreasing the risk of attackers compromising the network.
- --Mesh Network  devices don&#39;t need to communicate directly with the central hub and every device can operate as a repeater and pass the signal onto another device. Allows greater distance coverage and won&#39;t fail due to lack of redundancy.
- --High levels of interoperability  Z-Wave alliance enforces strict standards making each device widely compatible with other devices, making it ideal for an expanding IoT network.

## Software

- --Software on the nodes will use the data collected by it&#39;s components to determine when and how long to open the valves for watering. This can include soil moisture getting to a certain level, the last watering time getting too high or a manual command being issued from Alexa or the SmartThings app.
- --Samsung&#39;s SmartThings Hub will allow us to use their software to issue basic commands and use automation with our connected devices, eliminating the requirement for custom made software on the hub and spending money and time on databases.

### Data Types

| Name | Data Type | Description |
| --- | --- | --- |
| NodeID | String | Primary key so each node can easily be modified |
| MoistureLevel | Float | Variable used for automatic watering if the soil gets too dry |
| LastWateringTime | Integer | Variable used to make sure there is not too much/too little time left inbetween waterings |
| TimeOpen | Float | Time valve is open, used to ensure watering doesn&#39;t last too long |
| ValveName | String | An easily memorable and sayable description of the specific valve, to allow voice commands to be issued to a specific valve. |
| DateTime | Date | The current date and time. This is necessary for multiple reasons such as different evaporation rates in the day and night, seasonal watering preferences. |

## Voice Control

Using the Amazon Echo, the user will be able to issue voice commands to the Alexa smart assistant to interact with the sprinkler nodes. This can be achieved through either the Samsung SmartThings integration of Alexa, or through creating a custom Alexa skill that responds to a custom range of commands in order to perform set actions. Some examples of these could be:

**I:** _&quot;Alexa, water the tulips for 30 seconds&quot;_

**O:** _&quot;Okay! Watering the tulips.&quot; _ This would activate a specific valve placed near the tulips in the garden.

**I:** _&quot;Alexa, put sprinklers to sleep for 1 week&quot;_

**O:** _&quot;Okay, sprinklers will not activate for 7 days&quot; _ This would stop the sprinklers from automatically watering for 1 week. Useful if there&#39;s a hosepipe ban, or there&#39;s some other reason you may not want the garden watering like having a garden party and not wanting your guests to be sprayed.

## Security and Privacy

- --Samsung likely collect metadata (Solution is not to use SmartThings  Trading convenience for privacy)
- --Samsung will likely collect telemetry and metadata of your use of their SmartThings products. You are trading convenience and the cost of servers for privacy here, so the best alternative would be to use private home servers.
- --If your Samsung account was hacked then your IoT network would be exposed to attackers. The best solution here is to secure your Samsung account well with a strong password and enable 2-Factory authentication.
- --Echo speaker could be abused to continuously and unnecessarily request the plants to be watered. Cound be countered by adding voice recognition for only trusted voices or a daily limit to how many times the speaker can activate the sprinklers.
- --All data is transferred over HTTPS and/or the secure Z-Wave standard using AES-128 encryption.
